    "summary": "The Numantine War (143–133 BC) was the final and most tenacious phase of Rome's long struggle to subdue the Celtiberian tribes of Hispania, centered on the fortified city of Numantia in what is now northern Spain. The Numantines, despite being massively outnumbered, inflicted repeated humiliations on Roman armies — including forcing entire legions to pass under the yoke in shameful surrender — before being subdued by Scipio Aemilianus.\n\nScipio Aemilianus, the destroyer of Carthage, was given special command and methodically besieged Numantia with a circumvallation of walls and towers, starving the city into submission in 133 BC. The surviving Numantines chose mass suicide or death over surrender. The fall of Numantia effectively completed Roman control of Hispania. The war's outcome influenced Tiberius Gracchus, who had witnessed the shameful Roman capitulations as a young officer and later launched his agrarian reforms partly in response to the social disruption caused by prolonged frontier warfare.",
